eu.excitement.entailment.core.utilities.immutable

Interface ImmutableMap<K,V>

  • Type Parameters:
    K - the map's key type
    V - the map's elements type
    All Superinterfaces:
    java.io.Serializable
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    ImmutableMapWrapper

    public interface ImmutableMap<K,V>
extends java.io.Serializable
    Represents an immutable map.

    This interface is similar to java.util.Map except that it has no methods to change any thing in the map.

    Note: an ImmutableMap may be non-thread-safe. For example, when using , and the underlying map is LinkedHashMap, and it is access-ordered, then even read operations may be non-thread-safe.

    Author:
    Asher Stern

      • getMutableCopy

        java.util.Map<K,V> getMutableCopy()
        Returns a mutable copy of the map. That copy is hard copy. Changing it does not change the original map.

        There is no guarantee about the returned map's type. It is only known that it implements java.util.Map

        Returns:
        a java.util.Map which is a deep copy of this map.

      • getImmutableCopy

        ImmutableMap<K,V> getImmutableCopy()
        Returns a deep copy of the map. After calling this method, the caller has two maps, and the elements' reference exist twice in each map.
        Returns:
        an ImmutableMap which is copy of this map.
